{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15026"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15026"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.07,0.1,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116014"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7714"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98010"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"8122"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18849"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116014"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDrug handling by the kidney involves multiple processes including filtration, secretion, reabsorption, and metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes drug handling by the kidney?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proximal tubular cells concentrate drugs during reabsorption making them vulnerable to toxicity","Drug metabolism occurs minimally in renal tissue","Medullary hypoxia protects against drug toxicity","Drug secretion occurs mainly in collecting ducts","Urinary pH has no effect on drug excretion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproximal tubular cells concentrate drugs during reabsorption making them vulnerable to toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because these cells actively reabsorb filtered substances, leading to high intracellular drug concentrations that can cause cellular damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug metabolism occurs minimally in renal tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the kidney contains significant drug-metabolizing enzymes including cytochrome P450. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedullary hypoxia protects against drug toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect since the hypoxic environment actually makes cells more susceptible to toxic injury. \u003Cstrong\u003EDrug secretion occurs mainly in collecting ducts\u003C/strong\u003E is wrong because drug secretion primarily occurs in the proximal tubules through specific transport systems. \u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary pH has no effect on drug excretion\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as urinary pH manipulation is an important therapeutic strategy in managing certain drug overdoses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding renal drug handling is crucial for predicting drug toxicity and developing strategies for enhanced drug elimination in overdose situations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Proximal tubular cells are vulnerable to drug toxicity due to extensive reabsorption and concentrating effects","The kidney contains significant drug-metabolizing enzymes including cytochrome P450","Drug secretion occurs primarily in the proximal tubules through specific transport systems","Urinary pH manipulation can enhance elimination of certain drugs based on their acid-base properties"],"references":["Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Masereeuw R, Russel FG. Mechanisms and clinical implications of renal drug excretion. Drug Metab Rev. 2001 Aug-Nov;33(3-4):299-351. doi: 10.1081/dmr-120000654. PMID: 11768771.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98010"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15026"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98010"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T10:27:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T10:28:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7714"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116014"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt